<h2>A dive into an ancient shojou manga</h2>
<p>Welcome to my review of Basara ! It is a pretty long series, containing 27 volumes, and I only read about 10 volumes, because it feels a bit too much to read all of this at once. Thus, it's very probable that I finish the remaining volumes in a near future, but it'll be after I finish some of the series I really want to discover. Anyway, let's dive into the review !</p>

<h3>Story</h3>
<p>I had a bit of troubles in the beginning to follow the story at the beginning, because of how blurry the events are. In fact, I didn't even understand who really survived between Sarasa and Tatara, since both look quite similar, and thus it was difficult to tell what was happening. Hopefully, after the first volume, the story becomes clear, and it is easy to tell what's the main plot, what Sarasa has to do, and who is helping her. <br>
This minor setback aside, the plot is divided in arcs. Some of them follow a classical story scheme of a character evolving through difficulty, while others are completely different, such as the island where Sarasa and Shuri meet for a while. These latter arcs are the most interesting ones, because they show the relationships evolve, and various subjects are covered, is it politics or medicine. <br>
My favorite arc would be the one with the false Blue King, since both Sarasa and Shuri work together, and they encounter a lot of new characters that remain in the next chapters, and are quite interesting. It is also because even if the king's is a main subject, it is not always shown blatantly, and violence is almost always metaphoric, implicit or hidden. And still, the ambient danger is palpable, violence is everywhere.<br>
I would only say that sometimes, the sudden turns of events are a bit weird, and feel to come out of nowhere. The battle between pirates and red king, for example, ends with a forbidden mountain erupting from water and helping people... In fact I'm not even sure it's exactly what happened, because I find that turnarounds like these are not easily understandable. Hopefully, they are not common, and everything is mostly fine.</p>

<h3>Characters</h3>
<p>The characters are divided in 3 categories: the villains, the heroes, and Ageha. The villains are all despicable, because they are violent and only seek power, and this includes Shuri. The heroes are caring and would die for Tatara, and eventually, Ageha is somewhere in between, useful for everyone and mysterious as always. This is a pretty simple yet efficient way to build up characters, and allows some of them to be ambiguous, since they are on both sides.<br>
Regarding Sarasa, I think that I was wrongly considering her at the beginning. Since her appearance made her look like a grown-up woman already, I expected her to be mature, smart etc, but I think she is way younger than this, and she has never experienced the world before living as Tatara. When considering this, it makes her a very endearing and cute character, who discovers life and love, as well as obstacles, all at the same time while on an adventure she did not chose to join. She slowly grows mentally and physically through the manga, and at Volume 10, she has become incredibly responsible and discerning. She manages to hold two personalities, Sarasa and Tatara, even if she is still mentally weaker when embodying herself.<br>
Shuri, on the other side of the border, truly has only one personality, and I despise it deeply. As the Red King, he does nothing but think about his own power and future, without taking in account the people around him, and considering the population as useless persons. As Shuri, he represents really well this masculinity and virility of old stories, saying dumb things like "All women love when I do this", thank you so much Yuna for punching him in the face.<br>
The close relatives of Sarasa is always so kind that, even for me, it's a relief to see them appear. Nagi especially, holds a very interesting vibe of protector and professor. I love him as much as Ageha, since they both have long hair lmao.<br>
Now onto the most important character, appearing in all volumes, maybe all chapters: Shinbashi ! This cute little ball of feathers is sooooo adorable, and he even has a story, and he has kind of a diary that explains what he does when living on Sarasa's shoulder ! I think he might be surprisingly the most sweet character, even if Sarasa's romance and feelings are awesome too.</p>

<h3>Visuals</h3>
<p>I found the style of the author very refined, yet so chaotic as the same time. The lines are clear, but sometimes the amount of details add up to create a mess of blurry shapes. What I loved to discover is the quality of graphics beside the main subjects. The background is often very detailed, the covers are very beautiful, in short the overall setting of the frames is well designed to make the whole thing very smooth. I love it.</p>

<h3>Conclusion</h3>
<p>I already knew that I loved old media, and this one only confirmed my thoughts. Apart from the characters, that may feel outdated or a very young, I find the overall work very modern and sometimes even better, looking at the attention the author gave to his manga. I will surely continue to read later, and I must say the manga has a good feeling, so I would grade it with a 8/10.</p>
